SIMPLE: grayling
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grayling
<hw>Gray"ling</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Gray</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A European fish
(<spn>Thymallus vulgaris</spn>), allied to the trout, but having a very
broad dorsal fin; -- called also <altname>umber</altname>. It inhabits
cold mountain streams, and is valued as a game fish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And here and there a lusty trout,⟦br⟧
And here and there a grayling.</q> <rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An American fish of the genus
<gen>Thymallus</gen>, having similar habits to the above; one species
(<spn>T. Ontariensis</spn>), inhabits several streams in Michigan;
another (<spn>T. montanus</spn>), is found in the Yellowstone
region.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grayness</ent>⟦br⟧
